	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I only had a GBA and a GBA SP (I not only have the SP). When I was little I didn't have a GameBoy  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_cry.gif" alt=":cry:" title="Crying or Very sad" /> 
<br />Fortunately things are fixed now.
<br />The GBASP screen is pretty good because it has its built-in light. When playing with sun-light instead, it can often become annoying because it works less good, and the built-in light won't change that at all. So if you have the choise between a dark place and use the light, or a light place and don't use the light, I'd rather pick the dark place unless I'm afraid the battery goes out too quickly or something.
<br />The original GBA had a screen better suited to play in light places, if I remember correctly, but in the dark you simply couldn't play.
<br />
<br />Tokumaru : Wich game(s) are you talking about of being so bad on the GBC ? My Dragon Warrior III card was extremly good, way better than the NES version even if both are technically 8-bit. I think aside of some Pokémon and Zelda games, GBC only games aren't here in a very big quantity. For the most part, they are GB/GBC compatible.
<br />
<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The gb magnifyer does sqat It makes the screen all wavy and has a bright light in the center with makes it blurry. What a waste of ten bucks.</div>
